00:09:12.910 --> 00:09:14.870
And now I just like to visit.

00:09:14.870 --> 00:09:17.370
Like we were talking about,
we were talking all morning

00:09:17.370 --> 00:09:19.620
off mic, so now we
get to talk into mics.

00:09:19.620 --> 00:09:22.530
But yeah, now the
whole pace of New York

00:09:22.530 --> 00:09:26.084
and just the circus of it,
I'm like wow, cool, got to go.

00:09:26.084 --> 00:09:27.750
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
Well you're here now

00:09:27.750 --> 00:09:31.830
for kind of a wild event,
supporting Cindy Lauper

00:09:31.830 --> 00:09:34.340
and the True Colors foundation.

00:09:34.340 --> 00:09:39.150
ANI DIFRANCO: Yeah, a benefit
to help an organization that

00:09:39.150 --> 00:09:45.060
tries to get homeless
queer youth a place to be

00:09:45.060 --> 00:09:46.595
and people to support them.

00:09:46.595 --> 00:09:48.720
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: It
brings me to the first topic

00:09:48.720 --> 00:09:50.095
that I wanted to
discuss with you

00:09:50.095 --> 00:09:53.250
which is, all of
these things speak

00:09:53.250 --> 00:09:56.970
to a career of proactivity.

00:09:56.970 --> 00:10:00.860
Looking back through
the years, you

00:10:00.860 --> 00:10:05.340
have always been at the pointed
end of the proactive stick.

00:10:05.340 --> 00:10:09.090
And I find that interesting in
the fact that a lot of artists

00:10:09.090 --> 00:10:10.590
are very reactive.

00:10:10.590 --> 00:10:13.560
An event would take place
and there's a response to it

00:10:13.560 --> 00:10:18.369
or a tribute to some tragedy
or some sort of reaction based.

00:10:18.369 --> 00:10:20.160
And I'm curious if you
can speak about what

00:10:20.160 --> 00:10:24.030
it's been like to always be in
that proactive space instead

00:10:24.030 --> 00:10:25.830
of just a simple reactive space?

00:10:25.830 --> 00:10:27.360
ANI DIFRANCO: Wow, I dig it.

00:10:27.360 --> 00:10:32.490
I dig the whole pointed
end of the stick.

00:10:32.490 --> 00:10:35.520
I mean, yeah, jeez.

00:10:35.520 --> 00:10:38.460
I mean I guess like
anybody I've just

00:10:38.460 --> 00:10:44.910
been trying to speak my truth,
my experience, my thoughts,

00:10:44.910 --> 00:10:49.470
my dreams, my perception
in my songs, in my writing.

00:10:49.470 --> 00:10:54.450
And I guess
personally I'm always

00:10:54.450 --> 00:10:58.720
compelled by art that
takes risks, you know?

00:10:58.720 --> 00:11:03.450
So I've always kind
of pushed myself.

00:11:03.450 --> 00:11:08.400
It used to be really hard
to be that in the beginning.

00:11:08.400 --> 00:11:12.851
You know, I used to, oh jeez,
who's going to be at the show

00:11:12.851 --> 00:11:13.350
tonight?

00:11:13.350 --> 00:11:16.590
And no, my mom, or [INAUDIBLE]?

00:11:16.590 --> 00:11:18.620
And what will happen
when I say this?

00:11:21.660 --> 00:11:26.005
And a lot happens when
you're jabbing at stuff.

00:11:28.570 --> 00:11:31.260
But I would say that the
most important thing that

00:11:31.260 --> 00:11:34.230
happened over the years was
that people came out of nowhere

00:11:34.230 --> 00:11:37.950
and said me too or
thank you, oh my God.

00:11:37.950 --> 00:11:42.210
And all of that, hearing
people repeatedly

00:11:42.210 --> 00:11:45.420
say I can't believe you
just said that, thank you,

00:11:45.420 --> 00:11:49.230
just meant so much
more than all the rest.

00:11:49.230 --> 00:11:53.220
So it's kind of encouraged
me to just let it go,

00:11:53.220 --> 00:11:56.730
all those ideas of what's
private or personal or

00:11:56.730 --> 00:11:58.860
inappropriate or
this or the other.

00:11:58.860 --> 00:12:00.420
It's like, it's all universal.

00:12:00.420 --> 00:12:02.732
It's, none of it's unique.

00:12:02.732 --> 00:12:04.440
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
It's curious that you

00:12:04.440 --> 00:12:06.330
said it used to be
more difficult for you

00:12:06.330 --> 00:12:09.720
because I would
almost think that now

00:12:09.720 --> 00:12:13.380
is a time period of difficulty
for anyone being proactive.

00:12:13.380 --> 00:12:18.510
There's so much tension and so
much pushback to any push that

00:12:18.510 --> 00:12:20.490
is there.

00:12:20.490 --> 00:12:22.380
Does that weigh in
at all when you're

00:12:22.380 --> 00:12:25.320
about to step up and make
a bold statement of like--

00:12:25.320 --> 00:12:28.206
you said before it
was the idea of oh,

00:12:28.206 --> 00:12:29.580
my mom's in the
audience, I don't

00:12:29.580 --> 00:12:31.650
want to run afoul of that.

00:12:31.650 --> 00:12:35.325
But now some fraction
of the world might be.

00:12:35.325 --> 00:12:37.950
ANI DIFRANCO: There's others in
the audience that are even more

00:12:37.950 --> 00:12:39.090
dangerous than mothers.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:50.480
I mean, I feel like it was
really good to just come out

00:12:50.480 --> 00:12:55.610
of the box with my mouth and
spirit open and just start.

00:12:55.610 --> 00:13:01.260
I mean when I was a teenager and
I started making my own songs,

00:13:01.260 --> 00:13:05.510
I started pushing against that
wall of acceptability and what

00:13:05.510 --> 00:13:08.810
you can and cannot say
and can and cannot be.

00:13:08.810 --> 00:13:11.840
And really early on I
just was like, F it.

00:13:11.840 --> 00:13:15.210
Just what's going
to happen to me?

00:13:15.210 --> 00:13:17.340
Let's find out.

00:13:17.340 --> 00:13:23.480
And 25, whatever it's
been, 30 years later,

00:13:23.480 --> 00:13:26.560
I'm in a great position now.

00:13:26.560 --> 00:13:31.420
I mean, I weeded out the
riffraff a long time ago.

00:13:31.420 --> 00:13:34.420
I think it's much
more difficult if you

00:13:34.420 --> 00:13:37.540
have a secret to let it go.

00:13:37.540 --> 00:13:40.780
If you've never had
secrets, it's easier.

00:13:40.780 --> 00:13:41.560
It's better.

00:13:41.560 --> 00:13:45.780
People used to ask me about
coming out or this or that.

00:13:45.780 --> 00:13:50.200
It's like, I was
not in anywhere.

00:13:50.200 --> 00:13:54.380
And I think that that, from
my experience, it's better.

00:13:54.380 --> 00:13:57.110
It's easier to do it that way.

00:13:57.110 --> 00:14:00.430
I had a young lady opening
up my shows recently

00:14:00.430 --> 00:14:06.700
who's had some success
with a song online.

00:14:06.700 --> 00:14:09.280
And she's a lovely young gal.

00:14:09.280 --> 00:14:12.490
And she's sort of just
embarking on a career in music.

00:14:12.490 --> 00:14:15.160
And she was saying--

00:14:15.160 --> 00:14:19.540
we were talking after one night
and she said, "I'm pro-choice

00:14:19.540 --> 00:14:22.660
but I'm so afraid.

00:14:22.660 --> 00:14:25.440
I come from a traditional
family, I this and I that."

00:14:25.440 --> 00:14:27.790
And I said, "Just say it.

00:14:27.790 --> 00:14:28.700
Just say it.

00:14:28.700 --> 00:14:30.880
The sooner you say
it, the better.

00:14:30.880 --> 00:14:34.450
Say who you are, what you
believe, what you think.

00:14:34.450 --> 00:14:38.060
Because from there, it
gets easier every day."

00:14:38.060 --> 00:14:40.360
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: I'm
going to change my plan now

00:14:40.360 --> 00:14:44.200
that you brought this up because
this idea of just saying it--

00:14:44.200 --> 00:14:46.960
I wanted to speak later in the
conversation about the idea

00:14:46.960 --> 00:14:50.140
of directness and
metaphor, but we sort of

00:14:50.140 --> 00:14:51.400
skipped ahead to that.

00:14:51.400 --> 00:14:55.120
In your music there's
use of metaphor,

00:14:55.120 --> 00:14:57.610
but where you
really get masterful

00:14:57.610 --> 00:15:00.580
is with just direct
statements of like you said,

00:15:00.580 --> 00:15:03.560
just taking it head on
and tackling it that way.

00:15:03.560 --> 00:15:07.030
And I'm curious if you can talk
about the choices of when you

00:15:07.030 --> 00:15:09.160
want to say something
in a very direct fashion

00:15:09.160 --> 00:15:12.880
or when you reach a little
deeper for metaphor to try

00:15:12.880 --> 00:15:16.277
and mask an idea or
bow an idea as it were.

00:15:16.277 --> 00:15:17.860
ANI DIFRANCO: Yeah,
yeah, yeah, right.

00:15:21.260 --> 00:15:26.080
I guess I just always had
maybe just such a burning.

00:15:26.080 --> 00:15:29.990
Every time I see
an Eastern medicine

00:15:29.990 --> 00:15:33.950
practitioner they say, oh, your
spleen, whoa with the spleen.

00:15:33.950 --> 00:15:35.420
I'm like yeah, I know.

00:15:35.420 --> 00:15:40.070
You should see my 20
records, spleen music.

00:15:40.070 --> 00:15:48.370
And it's just, I have such an
urgent need to, I don't know,

00:15:48.370 --> 00:15:53.980
beat back lies and
silences that often it

00:15:53.980 --> 00:15:57.850
drives me to just say it.

00:15:57.850 --> 00:16:02.050
I think that's just where
my music is coming from.

00:16:02.050 --> 00:16:06.850
Sometimes I'm
interested in, how could

00:16:06.850 --> 00:16:11.350
you say it without saying
it, or how could you say--

00:16:11.350 --> 00:16:15.850
but oftentimes the
direct route is

00:16:15.850 --> 00:16:17.770
what is most appealing to me.

00:16:17.770 --> 00:16:21.580
I used to get a lot of flack for
it, like we were talking about,

00:16:21.580 --> 00:16:24.490
a lot of resistance,
a lot of pushback.

00:16:24.490 --> 00:16:26.930
When you were forming
your question,

00:16:26.930 --> 00:16:31.030
I was remembering the first
time I went to Italy to play.

00:16:31.030 --> 00:16:33.850
We were talking earlier
about touring in Europe.

00:16:33.850 --> 00:16:38.960
And the first time I went to
Italy was probably 20 years ago

00:16:38.960 --> 00:16:43.990
and it was in an age of
flak that I was living in.

00:16:43.990 --> 00:16:47.050
And I remember the first
interview I did in Italy

00:16:47.050 --> 00:16:53.920
and the dude was like, "So
many artists, they say it

00:16:53.920 --> 00:16:54.850
but they don't say it.

00:16:54.850 --> 00:16:56.330
They say the little metaphor.

00:16:56.330 --> 00:16:57.180
They hint it.

00:16:57.180 --> 00:16:59.500
You just [GRUNTS],,
you just say it."

00:16:59.500 --> 00:17:01.660
And I was like, "That's good?

00:17:01.660 --> 00:17:03.370
You're saying that's good?"

00:17:03.370 --> 00:17:08.349
I'd never heard a positive
response to that before.

00:17:08.349 --> 00:17:11.230
I just remember that so
clearly that moment of,

00:17:11.230 --> 00:17:14.453
maybe somebody
thinks that's good.

00:17:14.453 --> 00:17:16.869
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: Well, and
it's curious with the things

00:17:16.869 --> 00:17:18.280
that you've chosen
to talk about.

00:17:18.280 --> 00:17:20.230
And we spoke with a
little bit about this

00:17:20.230 --> 00:17:24.220
before, as you said,
but I was immediately,

00:17:24.220 --> 00:17:27.010
in preparing for
this conversation,

00:17:27.010 --> 00:17:29.110
just went through
the entire catalog

00:17:29.110 --> 00:17:30.880
again of flashing back--

00:17:30.880 --> 00:17:33.190
ANI DIFRANCO: God
bless your heart.

00:17:33.190 --> 00:17:34.330
Live to tell the tale.

00:17:34.330 --> 00:17:35.580
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: I'm a fan.

00:17:35.580 --> 00:17:36.930
I'm a fan.

00:17:36.930 --> 00:17:38.740
But a couple of things
that caught with me

00:17:38.740 --> 00:17:39.970
were this directness.

00:17:39.970 --> 00:17:44.200
And I mentioned before
a song like "Gratitude".

00:17:44.200 --> 00:17:48.970
And recently of course #MeToo
has found a life online

00:17:48.970 --> 00:17:52.180
and this sort of
understanding of women

00:17:52.180 --> 00:17:54.400
not being alone in these
situations, and men

00:17:54.400 --> 00:17:56.790
as well in fact.

00:17:56.790 --> 00:17:59.830
But I immediately went
back to early '90s

00:17:59.830 --> 00:18:03.610
when "Gratitude" spoke
exactly to that topic.

00:18:03.610 --> 00:18:07.490
And another example would
be like "To the Teeth".

00:18:07.490 --> 00:18:09.820
This is something that is
decades old at this point

00:18:09.820 --> 00:18:13.420
but it's still
modern day prescient.

00:18:13.420 --> 00:18:16.840
When something happens in the
world that you have spoken

00:18:16.840 --> 00:18:20.750
or have tackled directly on
that flashes you back 10 years,

00:18:20.750 --> 00:18:23.980
20 years into your career,
how does that land for you?

00:18:23.980 --> 00:18:26.320
How does how do you
process something

00:18:26.320 --> 00:18:29.140
like #MeToo in light of the
fact that 20 years ago you

00:18:29.140 --> 00:18:33.240
were standing up shouting
exactly these words?

00:18:33.240 --> 00:18:37.290
ANI DIFRANCO: Yeah, sometimes
it's a little heart sickening.

00:18:37.290 --> 00:18:39.390
"To the Teeth"
that you mentioned

00:18:39.390 --> 00:18:43.470
is a song about gun
violence, a song

00:18:43.470 --> 00:18:49.160
I wrote, I don't know, pushing
20 years ago when I thought

00:18:49.160 --> 00:18:52.400
it was completely out of hand.

00:18:52.400 --> 00:18:58.455
So to pull that song out now and
play it is kind of devastating.

00:19:02.080 --> 00:19:04.630
But things do change.

00:19:04.630 --> 00:19:09.890
And often you think this
is just the way it is.

00:19:09.890 --> 00:19:12.310
We just have to accept
this is the way it is.

00:19:12.310 --> 00:19:14.470
And then overnight, it's not.

00:19:14.470 --> 00:19:18.310
And this #MeToo
moment that we're in,

00:19:18.310 --> 00:19:29.270
I think it really speaks to how
much the dominant culture sees

00:19:29.270 --> 00:19:37.328
women now compared to when I
was writing that song even.

00:19:37.328 --> 00:19:39.650
The fact that
we're hearing women

00:19:39.650 --> 00:19:46.218
give voice to their experience
as though it matters,

00:19:46.218 --> 00:19:52.320
because they're becoming
human in the dominant culture,

00:19:52.320 --> 00:19:56.310
and now we have to
accommodate that experience

00:19:56.310 --> 00:20:00.090
and those people and those
voices and those stories.

00:20:00.090 --> 00:20:04.230
It's one more voice in the
chorus, one more person

00:20:04.230 --> 00:20:06.030
with a seat at the table.

00:20:06.030 --> 00:20:07.980
And that's incredible.

00:20:07.980 --> 00:20:09.120
I've seen a lot change.

00:20:12.120 --> 00:20:19.930
I've seen the work of
feminism take hold around me.

00:20:19.930 --> 00:20:23.310
From when I was first
stomping around saying stuff

00:20:23.310 --> 00:20:25.980
in my songs, I've never--

00:20:25.980 --> 00:20:28.440
and I've actually,
on that tip, I've

00:20:28.440 --> 00:20:33.790
never felt a more
receptive world around me

00:20:33.790 --> 00:20:38.020
for a lot of my feminist ideas.

00:20:38.020 --> 00:20:43.030
So I actually am very
hopeful right now.

00:20:43.030 --> 00:20:46.510
I know it's a time
of great peril--

00:20:46.510 --> 00:20:51.310
and I don't mean to underplay
that-- and a time of great pain

00:20:51.310 --> 00:20:52.390
for a lot of people.

00:20:52.390 --> 00:20:54.670
But I think that
the possibilities,

00:20:54.670 --> 00:20:57.940
I think it's a
transformative moment

00:20:57.940 --> 00:21:01.669
we're in, especially
around gender politics.

00:21:01.669 --> 00:21:04.210
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: And there's
more of that on the new album

00:21:04.210 --> 00:21:07.660
"Binary", which by the way,
in addition to this incredibly

00:21:07.660 --> 00:21:12.220
proactive career, it's also
an incredibly prolific career

00:21:12.220 --> 00:21:13.360
in fact that--

00:21:13.360 --> 00:21:16.570
I read somewhere that it's
the 20th studio album,

00:21:16.570 --> 00:21:20.755
and I read somewhere else
that it was more than 20.

00:21:20.755 --> 00:21:21.960
20 albums?

00:21:21.960 --> 00:21:24.050
ANI DIFRANCO: 20, yeah,
I know, what the hell?

00:21:24.050 --> 00:21:24.880
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
That's amazing.

00:21:24.880 --> 00:21:26.440
ANI DIFRANCO: Yeah,
it's at least 20.

00:21:26.440 --> 00:21:29.770
There's 20 of those suckers.

00:21:29.770 --> 00:21:31.960
Yeah, I don't know,
a lot of songs.

00:21:31.960 --> 00:21:34.240
Kids changed the game though.

00:21:34.240 --> 00:21:37.810
I've slowed right down.

00:21:37.810 --> 00:21:40.840
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: But not
for lack of just still creating

00:21:40.840 --> 00:21:41.780
amazing artwork.

00:21:41.780 --> 00:21:43.970
There's a great album here.

00:21:43.970 --> 00:21:46.990
And more stuff speaking to
what we were talking about,

00:21:46.990 --> 00:21:49.480
"Immediately Play
God" jumps to mind.

00:21:49.480 --> 00:21:53.780
Maybe you could talk about that
song and the nexus and genesis

00:21:53.780 --> 00:21:54.280
of all that.

00:21:54.280 --> 00:21:57.580
ANI DIFRANCO:
Absolutely, thanks.

00:21:57.580 --> 00:21:59.860
Yeah, I mean, I started
writing that song

00:21:59.860 --> 00:22:01.570
as kind of a bragging--

00:22:01.570 --> 00:22:10.030
I was like, what if I was like
a cross between Howlin' Wolf

00:22:10.030 --> 00:22:13.720
and Missy Elliott, what
would I write right now?

00:22:13.720 --> 00:22:17.260
And I started
talking about my life

00:22:17.260 --> 00:22:19.300
as an emancipated teenager.

00:22:19.300 --> 00:22:25.200
I was on my own at 15,
and never got nothing

00:22:25.200 --> 00:22:27.480
from nobody kind of.

00:22:27.480 --> 00:22:32.940
And then the spleen took over.

00:22:32.940 --> 00:22:38.200
And something
inside me just felt,

00:22:38.200 --> 00:22:44.720
as I was writing this bragging
verse about how I'm not

00:22:44.720 --> 00:22:47.520
a child, and even
when I was a child,

00:22:47.520 --> 00:22:49.520
I didn't get a
chance to be a child.

00:22:49.520 --> 00:22:55.760
And I was contributing
in society.

00:22:55.760 --> 00:22:58.740
I was a part of
society real early on.

00:22:58.740 --> 00:23:02.240
And then my brain just sort of
flicked to that to, and so you

00:23:02.240 --> 00:23:05.270
cannot treat me like a child.

00:23:05.270 --> 00:23:10.700
You tell me what I can and
cannot do with my body,

00:23:10.700 --> 00:23:17.480
when I should reproduce,
if I must reproduce.

00:23:17.480 --> 00:23:23.450
This is the kind of
way that women still

00:23:23.450 --> 00:23:27.200
are treated in society as
though they are inferior,

00:23:27.200 --> 00:23:29.270
as though they are children.

00:23:29.270 --> 00:23:35.690
So I think of reproductive
freedom as a civil right.

00:23:35.690 --> 00:23:38.720
I think that we need to
talk about it that way,

00:23:38.720 --> 00:23:39.800
address it that way.

00:23:39.800 --> 00:23:44.450
I think we could use another
constitutional amendment

00:23:44.450 --> 00:23:46.840
to guarantee women civil rights.

00:23:49.800 --> 00:23:56.280
And so the song just sort
of mutated into a women's

00:23:56.280 --> 00:23:59.430
civil rights anthem.

00:23:59.430 --> 00:24:01.935
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
There's a lot of--

00:24:01.935 --> 00:24:05.460
and it speaks to the title
of the album "Binary".

00:24:05.460 --> 00:24:06.752
There's a lot of dual meaning.

00:24:06.752 --> 00:24:09.210
And I find it interesting in
that that story started in one

00:24:09.210 --> 00:24:11.500
place and ended in another.

00:24:11.500 --> 00:24:15.580
Talk about the concept of
the entirety of the album

00:24:15.580 --> 00:24:18.960
and being binary and what
that means, where that's

00:24:18.960 --> 00:24:19.980
coming from.

00:24:19.980 --> 00:24:22.695
ANI DIFRANCO: Yeah,
sure, here at Google.

00:24:25.530 --> 00:24:30.720
Binary to me, first
of all, is not--

00:24:30.720 --> 00:24:33.750
I'm not really talking
about either/or.

00:24:33.750 --> 00:24:35.290
I'm talking about both always.

00:24:39.846 --> 00:24:43.440
I had a run-in with the
internet a few years ago.

00:24:43.440 --> 00:24:47.640
It came and found me in my
house and bit my head off

00:24:47.640 --> 00:24:50.260
and chewed on it for a while.

00:24:50.260 --> 00:24:57.250
And that was sort
of the beginning

00:24:57.250 --> 00:25:02.320
of a lot of meditations
on consciousness for me.

00:25:02.320 --> 00:25:08.560
Oddly, these ones and zeros
came and changed my life

00:25:08.560 --> 00:25:10.910
and hurt me bad.

00:25:10.910 --> 00:25:18.750
And I started to look
at the whole world

00:25:18.750 --> 00:25:22.860
as made of
relationship, basically,

00:25:22.860 --> 00:25:26.160
that anything that looks
to be a singularity

00:25:26.160 --> 00:25:28.660
is really a relationship.

00:25:28.660 --> 00:25:33.040
Everything is two
things spinning.

00:25:33.040 --> 00:25:37.650
From our atomic structure to
the planets and the stars,

00:25:37.650 --> 00:25:40.260
there is this fundamental
design I think

00:25:40.260 --> 00:25:43.110
that is made of relationship.

00:25:43.110 --> 00:25:47.190
And I'm fascinated
by quantum physics.

00:25:47.190 --> 00:25:48.840
I don't understand
it, of course,

00:25:48.840 --> 00:25:51.360
but I like to read about it.

00:25:51.360 --> 00:25:53.310
And you know quantum
physicists, I

00:25:53.310 --> 00:26:00.040
think through a long
trajectory of masculine science

00:26:00.040 --> 00:26:03.100
have come back around to sort
of the reality of the mother

00:26:03.100 --> 00:26:06.070
that nothing exists on its own.

00:26:06.070 --> 00:26:08.720
Only in relationship do we--

00:26:08.720 --> 00:26:13.850
I mean, there's an infinite
field of possibilities

00:26:13.850 --> 00:26:18.220
until something is observed.

00:26:18.220 --> 00:26:21.460
And they will go on to tell
you that observing something

00:26:21.460 --> 00:26:25.970
affects it, that
observing is interacting.

00:26:25.970 --> 00:26:29.050
So with interaction
comes existence.

00:26:29.050 --> 00:26:31.000
I guess that's basically--

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:34.570
Then of course it's not
disconnected with my feminism.

00:26:34.570 --> 00:26:39.160
And I think that that kind of--

00:26:39.160 --> 00:26:42.760
the ways that my brain has been
spinning for the past few years

00:26:42.760 --> 00:26:45.320
kind of weaves
through this record.

00:26:45.320 --> 00:26:47.020
So that's why I
took that song title

00:26:47.020 --> 00:26:49.550
to title the whole record.

00:26:49.550 --> 00:26:51.970
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: Well it
goes even further than that,

00:26:51.970 --> 00:26:55.540
because this is a very
interactive record for you,

00:26:55.540 --> 00:26:57.100
I think, in the creation, right?

00:26:57.100 --> 00:26:59.560
There's a lot of
collaboration on this record,

00:26:59.560 --> 00:27:02.009
and even on the technical
side more collaboration

00:27:02.009 --> 00:27:03.550
than I think you've
done in the past.

00:27:03.550 --> 00:27:08.050
How was the process of making
"Binary" different or familiar

00:27:08.050 --> 00:27:11.180
or unfamiliar or taking a risk?

00:27:11.180 --> 00:27:14.530
ANI DIFRANCO: Yeah, well often
I make records by myself.

00:27:14.530 --> 00:27:17.860
I crawl into a hole depending
on what's happening in my life

00:27:17.860 --> 00:27:20.080
and make a little record.

00:27:20.080 --> 00:27:25.120
Or I track the songs with my
band but then I futz on my own

00:27:25.120 --> 00:27:27.730
and finish it or
something solitary.

00:27:27.730 --> 00:27:33.340
The record right before this
I did a lot in the wee hours

00:27:33.340 --> 00:27:37.330
when the kids were
sleeping in headphones.

00:27:37.330 --> 00:27:40.650
This time, my youngest is four.

00:27:43.630 --> 00:27:47.110
I needed to re-enter
the world and interact

00:27:47.110 --> 00:27:49.870
with adults and creative
beings and people who

00:27:49.870 --> 00:27:53.020
would bring ideas to
the table other than me.

00:27:53.020 --> 00:27:56.230
So I tracked the tunes
with not just my core

00:27:56.230 --> 00:28:02.110
band, rhythm section, but a few
other musicians that I love,

00:28:02.110 --> 00:28:04.450
Ivan Neville in New
Orleans where I live

00:28:04.450 --> 00:28:10.030
and Jenny Scheinman, a beautiful
violinist from out west.

00:28:10.030 --> 00:28:11.740
And then I just
started calling up

00:28:11.740 --> 00:28:14.110
a lot of other brilliant
friends that I have.

00:28:14.110 --> 00:28:16.550
I just didn't want to be alone.

00:28:16.550 --> 00:28:20.800
I wanted community
back in my life.

00:28:20.800 --> 00:28:23.770
So there's a lot of
beautiful players.

00:28:23.770 --> 00:28:26.290
And I had this kind of
experience of the best

00:28:26.290 --> 00:28:30.010
Christmas ever again
and again where

00:28:30.010 --> 00:28:33.220
I sent Justin Vernon a
track and then my present

00:28:33.220 --> 00:28:35.170
comes in the mail,
bing, and I get

00:28:35.170 --> 00:28:38.050
to open it up and see
this beautiful chorus

00:28:38.050 --> 00:28:39.520
that he sang on my song.

00:28:39.520 --> 00:28:43.720
It's just the most
wonderful presents came back

00:28:43.720 --> 00:28:45.970
to me from my friends.

00:28:45.970 --> 00:28:48.700
And then I even went
one step further

00:28:48.700 --> 00:28:51.070
than I've ever gone which
is to have somebody else mix

00:28:51.070 --> 00:28:52.300
the damn thing.

00:28:52.300 --> 00:28:54.130
I've always just,
oh, I can do this.

00:28:54.130 --> 00:28:55.930
OK, this sounds good, right?

00:28:59.110 --> 00:29:07.630
So my records over the years
are unique and expressive.

00:29:07.630 --> 00:29:14.650
But having brought a creative
mind like Tchad Blake

00:29:14.650 --> 00:29:16.970
to into this project to mix it--

00:29:16.970 --> 00:29:18.500
remotely, once again.

00:29:18.500 --> 00:29:22.910
I just sent him raw tracks
and I got back mixes--

00:29:22.910 --> 00:29:24.960
was breathtaking for me.

00:29:24.960 --> 00:29:28.580
It was like, oh wow,
what if you're not crazy

00:29:28.580 --> 00:29:30.680
and you didn't just
write the songs

00:29:30.680 --> 00:29:36.680
and you came in with an
objectivity and a skill

00:29:36.680 --> 00:29:38.920
that I will never
achieve in mixing?

00:29:38.920 --> 00:29:40.670
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
Different perspective.

00:29:40.670 --> 00:29:44.060
ANI DIFRANCO: A
different perspective.

00:29:44.060 --> 00:29:44.990
What a gift.

00:29:44.990 --> 00:29:49.620
Wow, you can really do things
in mixing, as it turns out.

00:29:49.620 --> 00:29:53.980
So I don't think I'll
ever go back to--

00:29:53.980 --> 00:29:56.870
but you know, I've been
thinking about it lately,

00:29:56.870 --> 00:30:01.010
the emancipated minor thing
when you're just, I got this,

00:30:01.010 --> 00:30:04.130
and you're just taking
care of everything.

00:30:04.130 --> 00:30:09.020
Now I'm 47 and I'm like, I
don't have to do that anymore.

00:30:09.020 --> 00:30:12.209
It took me a while to let go.

00:30:12.209 --> 00:30:13.750
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
It's interesting.

00:30:13.750 --> 00:30:18.960
It also, I found that in
listening to the record,

00:30:18.960 --> 00:30:22.940
it's super broad in
style and approach.

00:30:22.940 --> 00:30:26.500
And there's some stuff on
here that is very classic Ani

00:30:26.500 --> 00:30:28.770
DiFranco style.

00:30:28.770 --> 00:30:34.860
There are other tracks on here
that are nearly hip-hop songs.

00:30:34.860 --> 00:30:39.240
And then "Spider" is
kind of the other end

00:30:39.240 --> 00:30:43.410
of that spectrum in a very
indie rock kind of way.

00:30:43.410 --> 00:30:45.660
Where did the diversity
come from from this album?

00:30:45.660 --> 00:30:48.510
Was it out of this
collaboration or were

00:30:48.510 --> 00:30:50.520
there trigger moments
that were like, hey,

00:30:50.520 --> 00:30:52.594
I'm going to go in this
direction for a reason?

00:30:52.594 --> 00:30:54.302
I'm wondering if you
could speak to that.

00:30:54.302 --> 00:30:55.820
ANI DIFRANCO: Yeah,
I mean, I like--

00:30:55.820 --> 00:30:57.420
and I've been hearing
it from others

00:30:57.420 --> 00:31:02.670
that the sort of diversity
of the sounds on this record.

00:31:02.670 --> 00:31:07.260
And I think that has to do
with Tchad and with the people

00:31:07.260 --> 00:31:10.470
that I worked with,
the musicians helping

00:31:10.470 --> 00:31:17.190
me translate my songs fully,
helping me manifest them fully.

00:31:17.190 --> 00:31:23.550
I think that I've always
written really in a diverse way.

00:31:23.550 --> 00:31:26.350
I never kind of want to
write the same song twice,

00:31:26.350 --> 00:31:28.470
so I'm always, let
me write a song

00:31:28.470 --> 00:31:32.790
standing on my head with
a bucket on each foot

00:31:32.790 --> 00:31:35.940
and see what that
turns out like.

00:31:35.940 --> 00:31:36.930
So I've done that all.

00:31:36.930 --> 00:31:40.620
But then I think
then I just play it

00:31:40.620 --> 00:31:44.310
like I always do on
whatever's sitting around.

00:31:44.310 --> 00:31:48.830
And then I just sort of mix
it so you can hear everything.

00:31:48.830 --> 00:31:52.980
But I think when other
people come in and enhance

00:31:52.980 --> 00:31:57.810
the creativity that exists
in the seed of a song

00:31:57.810 --> 00:31:59.550
and they say, well,
this sounds to me

00:31:59.550 --> 00:32:05.280
like we should go over here,
and look, I have an ark.

00:32:05.280 --> 00:32:07.110
We can go over there.

00:32:07.110 --> 00:32:10.860
And so I think that these
songs were more fully

00:32:10.860 --> 00:32:15.706
realized in their differences
than maybe on other records.

00:32:15.706 --> 00:32:17.580
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: Well
I'm happy to hear it

00:32:17.580 --> 00:32:21.024
because it does take a lot
of the music in a new place.

00:32:21.024 --> 00:32:22.440
And speaking of
the new place, you

00:32:22.440 --> 00:32:24.630
spoke a little bit of
the internet coming

00:32:24.630 --> 00:32:26.460
to bite you a few years ago.

00:32:26.460 --> 00:32:29.020
Skipping past that, I
know that for "Binary"

00:32:29.020 --> 00:32:30.589
there are some videos.

00:32:30.589 --> 00:32:32.880
And we were speaking about
it before, these were things

00:32:32.880 --> 00:32:34.609
that you had sort of
independently done.

00:32:34.609 --> 00:32:36.150
I wonder if you
could talk about what

00:32:36.150 --> 00:32:38.340
it's like to be, as
we've said before,

00:32:38.340 --> 00:32:41.220
sort of an old-school
artist approaching that way

00:32:41.220 --> 00:32:43.080
and being thrust
into the situation

00:32:43.080 --> 00:32:46.590
to where maybe now just
an album's not enough?

00:32:46.590 --> 00:32:51.090
ANI DIFRANCO: Yeah,
that seems to be true.

00:32:51.090 --> 00:32:52.680
I think I'm just a folk singer.

00:32:52.680 --> 00:32:55.860
I'm a working musician and
playing live for people,

00:32:55.860 --> 00:32:59.140
just gathering with people.

00:32:59.140 --> 00:33:06.200
I think the sort of
fundamental reality of music

00:33:06.200 --> 00:33:09.360
as a social act is
really how I feel it.

00:33:09.360 --> 00:33:10.970
And that's what inspires me.

00:33:10.970 --> 00:33:17.780
And so I think I'm most inspired
on stage, spending an hour

00:33:17.780 --> 00:33:19.610
and a half, two
hours with people

00:33:19.610 --> 00:33:25.370
and the kind of connections that
you make and the kind of less

00:33:25.370 --> 00:33:27.650
alone that we all
feel when we walk out

00:33:27.650 --> 00:33:30.110
of there and the kind of--

00:33:30.110 --> 00:33:33.950
that is what I live for.

00:33:33.950 --> 00:33:36.410
And the rest of
it, I don't know.

00:33:36.410 --> 00:33:38.690
It's all changed around me.

00:33:38.690 --> 00:33:41.000
And I'd be the last
to really know.

00:33:41.000 --> 00:33:44.750
I think at one point in
the '90s people were like,

00:33:44.750 --> 00:33:47.040
Ani, how do you do it?

00:33:47.040 --> 00:33:49.100
Show us how it's done.

00:33:49.100 --> 00:33:52.430
And I'm so far from
being that guy anymore.

00:33:52.430 --> 00:33:53.930
I'm an old lady.

00:33:53.930 --> 00:33:59.780
And I have no idea
how you utilize

00:33:59.780 --> 00:34:06.020
the technology and the media
to have a career in music

00:34:06.020 --> 00:34:07.880
in the 21st century.

00:34:07.880 --> 00:34:12.530
I just know that I like
to play for people live.

00:34:12.530 --> 00:34:16.790
And if I can just do that and
pay my rent until I'm dead,

00:34:16.790 --> 00:34:17.290
I'll be OK.

00:34:17.290 --> 00:34:18.915
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
And you were saying

00:34:18.915 --> 00:34:20.630
before that you
felt very flattered

00:34:20.630 --> 00:34:23.449
by your audiences enjoying
that moment with you

00:34:23.449 --> 00:34:25.237
and participating in
that moment with you.

00:34:25.237 --> 00:34:27.320
I think it's very common
for people to go to shows

00:34:27.320 --> 00:34:29.420
and the first thing that
happens is the phone comes out.

00:34:29.420 --> 00:34:30.503
ANI DIFRANCO: Yeah, right.

00:34:30.503 --> 00:34:33.469
We were talking
earlier this morning

00:34:33.469 --> 00:34:36.830
and I was telling
Matthew I have noticed

00:34:36.830 --> 00:34:43.880
this last couple of months
being on the road, no phones,

00:34:43.880 --> 00:34:46.580
no phones in the audience,
almost no phones,

00:34:46.580 --> 00:34:50.179
which is noticeable.

00:34:50.179 --> 00:34:54.409
I feel like my audience
were sort of the last

00:34:54.409 --> 00:34:58.460
to live the show
through the phone.

00:34:58.460 --> 00:35:03.960
And when it came into the space
of my shows, I just was like,

00:35:03.960 --> 00:35:08.090
I guess this is the world now.

00:35:08.090 --> 00:35:13.400
There's nowhere to go that this
is not the world, so all right.

00:35:13.400 --> 00:35:19.610
And then these last few months,
I got the feeling like people

00:35:19.610 --> 00:35:21.130
have had enough.

00:35:21.130 --> 00:35:22.180
They've had enough.

00:35:22.180 --> 00:35:24.650
It's like, I want
an hour and a half

00:35:24.650 --> 00:35:28.670
of being in a place and a time
with the people that I'm with.

00:35:28.670 --> 00:35:32.960
And it was like,
look at you guys.

00:35:32.960 --> 00:35:37.300
There hasn't been one
glowing blue face tonight.

00:35:37.300 --> 00:35:40.690
"Con-grat-u-fucking-la-tions",
we're all here.

00:35:40.690 --> 00:35:42.890
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
Maybe the escapism

00:35:42.890 --> 00:35:46.940
that the phone initially
served is found again

00:35:46.940 --> 00:35:48.620
in putting the phone
away and actually

00:35:48.620 --> 00:35:49.220
being a part of the experience.

00:35:49.220 --> 00:35:50.600
ANI DIFRANCO: Yeah,
well we got deep.

00:35:50.600 --> 00:35:51.230
We got deep.

00:35:51.230 --> 00:35:53.480
You guys missed the
whole conversation that

00:35:53.480 --> 00:35:55.850
meant anything, because yeah--

00:35:55.850 --> 00:35:56.150
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
Well I hope not.

00:35:56.150 --> 00:35:57.899
ANI DIFRANCO: --what
going on in new music

00:35:57.899 --> 00:36:02.460
and who are the groundbreaking
young artists of today?

00:36:02.460 --> 00:36:05.570
And of course
Petah will teach me

00:36:05.570 --> 00:36:07.910
everything I need to know
eventually about that.

00:36:07.910 --> 00:36:14.540
But we were wondering
together if this absorption

00:36:14.540 --> 00:36:20.711
into the gizmos, this endless
distraction and entertainment

00:36:20.711 --> 00:36:26.270
has prevented a generation or
two of groundbreaking music.

00:36:26.270 --> 00:36:27.560
You are not bored.

00:36:27.560 --> 00:36:30.800
